definition.value: A chlorobenzoic acid that is benzoic acid in which the ring hydrogens at positions 2 and 4 are substituted by chloro groups.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 4-chlorophenyl group.

The simplest carboxylic acid, containing a single carbon. Occurs naturally in various sources including the venom of bee and ant stings, and is a useful organic synthetic reagent. Principally used as a preservative and antibacterial agent in livestock feed. Induces severe metabolic acidosis and ocular injury in human subjects.
An aminobenzoic acid in which the amino group is para to the carboxy group.
An aminobenzoic acid that is benzoic acid having a single amino substituent located at position 2. It is a metabolite produced in L-tryptophan-kynurenine pathway in the central nervous system.
A monohydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of salicylic acid.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is benzoic acid carrying a hydroxy substituent at C-4 of the benzene ring.

A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is benzoic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3. It has been isolated from Taxus baccata. It is used as an intermediate in the synthesis of plasticisers, resins, pharmaceuticals, etc.
A 3-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is propionic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 2 is substituted by a phenyl group, and one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a hydroxy group.
A short-chain saturated fatty acid comprising ethane attached to the carbon of a carboxy group.
A tricarboxylic acid that is propane-1,2,3-tricarboxylic acid bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 2. It is an important metabolite in the pathway of all aerobic organisms.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is butane in which one of the terminal methyl groups has been oxidised to a carboxy group.
A haloacetic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by fluorine.
A C6, straight-chain saturated fatty acid.
A trihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydroxy groups are at positions 3, 4, and 5.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from one of the carboxy groups of succinic acid.
An organic sodium salt that is the disodium salt of betamethasone phosphate.
A C4-dicarboxylate that is the Z-isomer of but-2-enedioate(2-)
An acetylenic compound that is acetylene in which the hydrogens are replaced by carboxy groups.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of butynedioic acid.
A sulfobenzoic acid in which the sulfonic acid and carboxylic acid groups are in a para-relationship.
A monochlorobenzoic acid having the chloro group at the 2-position.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid in which the two carboxy groups are separated by a single methylene group.
An optically active form of malic acid having (R)-configuration.
An optically active form of malic acid having (S)-configuration.
A phthalate that is the conjugate base of phthalic acid.

A benzenedicarboxylic acid that is benzene substituted by carboxy groups at position 1 and 3. One of three possible isomers of benzenedicarboxylic acid, the others being phthalic and terephthalic acids.
